1) Employee Participation;
2) Process Safety Information;
3) Process Hazard Analysis (PHA);
4) Standard Operating Procedures;
5) Training;
6) Contractors;
7) Pre-startup Safety Review;
8) Mechanical Integrity with Preventive Maintenance;
9) Hazardous Work Permits;
10)Management of Change;
11)Incident or Potential Catastrophic Event Investigation;
12)Emergency Response;
13)Compliance Audits; and
14)Trade Secrets.

These fourteen (14) individual elements of this prevention program work together to prevent accidental chemical releases. Marathon and its employees are committed to the standards required by these management programs. In addition to the above elements, Marathon also has specific prevention measures that are employed as part of the Terminal's operating procedures and engineering and administrative controls to help identify/contain/control a release, and reduce the consequences of a release. These are briefly summarized as follows:

General Risk Reduction and Safety Measures

-Engineering and construction in accordance with recognized industry and company standards;
-Equipment properly designed with protection from overpressure (pressure safety relief valves, etc.);
-Updated technical drawings, Piping & Instrument Diagrams and Process/Block Flow Diagrams;
-Operating systems monitored and controlled by trained Operators;
-Computerized monitoring and control of process operation;
-Redundant control systems with battery

back-ups;
-Automatic and manual shutdown devices for critical systems;
-Scheduled inspection and testing of instruments, analyzers, and safety devices;
-Limited/secured facility access;
-Regular safety meetings and safety awareness programs;
-Routinely scheduled safety inspections and audits; and 
-Frequent unit surveillance by operators.

General Release Mitigation

-Automatic and remotely operated shut-offs to limit release quantity;
-Strategically located valves to isolate leaks;
-Hydrocarbon detectors at key areas to warn of a chemical release; and
-Fire monitors installed at the butane storage vessel and offload area.

General Emergency Response

-Emergency alert system;
-Periodic emergency training for employees;
-Communication systems with local emergency responders and regulatory agencies; and
-Emergency drills with Terminal personnel, regulatory agencies, and community emergency responders to enhance response skills and coordination among agencies.

Further, the Tampa LP Terminal complies with the National Fire Protection Association's (NFPA's) Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG) Code (NFPA-58) requirements for LP Gas storage. In addition to the presence of appropriate controls to prevent possible releases of butane, a Facility Response Plan (FRP) is in place for the Facility and response activities are coordinated with Tampa Fire Rescue and Hillsborough County Office of Emergency Management.

C. FIVE YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY

The Tampa LP Terminal has an excellent record of accident prevention. The Terminal keeps records for all incidental and significant chemical releases inclusive of any root cause analyses and associated, follow-up actions. This is a "new" butane blending process; consequently, there have been no accidents within the past five (5) years resulting from the chemical release of materials covered under the EPA RMP regulation.

